<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 5 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER ES60-5 - DISASSEMBLE - INPUT
        SHAFT
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="3">
        <title>INPUT SHAFT</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After removing the input shaft bearing cap from the transmission, place it on a workbench
                with the open side down (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301238">Figure 38</hotlnk>). Tap the edges of the cap with a rubber mallet until the
                bearing race falls out. Remove the spacer and oil baffle. Remove the oil seal and replace it with a new
                one.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301238" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301238" filename="../figg13/g1301238.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 38. Input Shaft</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the input shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301239">Figure 39</hotlnk>). The hole in the center allows lubricant to flow to the
                pocket bearing. Make sure it is free from contaminants and other obstructions.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301239" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301239" filename="../figg13/g1301239.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 39. Check for Lubricant Flow</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press the bearing off the shaft and replace it with a new one (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301240">Figure 40</hotlnk>). It is good practice to always replace bearings during
                service.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301240" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301240" filename="../figg13/g1301240.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 40. Replace Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Wear safety glasses to protect your eyes from flying metal pieces when pulling components off
                        or pressing them onto a shaft.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
